05402nam a22008415i 9780812293845DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20172017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122938457 a10.9783/97808122938452doi  a(DE-B1597)481217  a(OCoLC)992454166  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aQL31.A9bN63 2017eb 7aHIS0360402bisacsh04a508.0922231 aNobles, Gregory, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJohn James Audubon :bThe Nature of the American Woodsman /cGregory Nobles. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b11 color, 14 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly American Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Creating Art, Science, and Self -- t1. Becoming Audubon, Becoming American -- t2. Hearing Birds, Heeding Their Call -- t3. Making an Odyssey for Art and Ornithology -- t4. Going into Business with The Birds of America -- t5. Struggling for Status in Science -- t6. Suffering for Science as the “American Woodsman” -- t7. Putting People into the Picture -- t8. Exploring the Ornithology of Ordinary People -- t9. Forging a Legacy, Finding a Discipline -- t10. Bringing Audubon Back to Life -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJohn James Audubon's The Birds of America stands as an unparalleled achievement in American art, a huge book that puts nature dramatically on the page. With that work, Audubon became one of the most adulated artists of his time, and America's first celebrity scientist.In this fresh approach to Audubon's art and science, Gregory Nobles shows us that Audubon's greatest creation was himself. A self-made man incessantly striving to secure his place in American society, Audubon made himself into a skilled painter, a successful entrepreneur, and a prolific writer, whose words went well beyond birds and scientific description. He sought status with the "gentlemen of science" on both sides of the Atlantic, but he also embraced the ornithology of ordinary people. In pursuit of popular acclaim in art and science, Audubon crafted an expressive, audacious, and decidedly masculine identity as the "American Woodsman," a larger-than-life symbol of the new nation, a role he perfected in his quest for transatlantic fame. Audubon didn't just live his life; he performed it.In exploring that performance, Nobles pays special attention to Audubon's stories, some of which—the murky circumstances of his birth, a Kentucky hunting trip with Daniel Boone, an armed encounter with a runaway slave—Audubon embellished with evasions and outright lies. Nobles argues that we cannot take all of Audubon's stories literally, but we must take them seriously. By doing so, we come to terms with the central irony of Audubon's true nature: the man who took so much time and trouble to depict birds so accurately left us a bold but deceptive picture of himself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aNaturalistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aOrnithologistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWildlife artistszUnited StatesvBiography. 4aAmerican History. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aAutobiography. 4aBiography. 4aBiology. 4aHistory of Science. 4aNatural History. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2017z9783110547764oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Pa